  "doc_id": "2859",
  "text": "Molecules near the liquid surface have a specific orientation. Spreading a monolayer on a clean water surface will produce a change in the orientation at the interface, so called the surface potential, which arises from the dipole moments of the film-forming materials, the change in orientation of head or tail group in the lipid monolayer and the water molecules in the subphase. Surface potential measurements can therefore provide information regarding the orientation of the film constituents [CITATION_1] [CITATION_2] . The value of surface potential rises from the dipole moment of both the lipid molecules and water and other molecules in the subphase during compression.",
